/Ernest_Rutherford,_1st_Baron_Rutherford_of_Nelson#cite_note-eb-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>In early work he discovered the concept of radioactive <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Half-life\" title=\"Half-life\">half-life<\/a>, proved that radioactivity involved the transmutation of one chemical element to another, and also differentiated and named <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Alpha_decay\" title=\"Alpha decay\">alpha<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Beta_particle\" title=\"Beta particle\">beta radiation<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ernest_Rutherford,_1st_Baron_Rutherford_of_Nelson#cite_note-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> This work was done at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/McGill_University\" title=\"McGill University\">McGill University<\/a> in Canada. It is the basis for the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Chemistry\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Chemistry\">Nobel Prize in Chemistry<\/a> he was awarded in 1908 \"for his investigations into the disintegration of the elements, and the chemistry of radioactive substances\",<sup id=\"cite_ref-nobelprize_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ernest_Rutherford,_1st_Baron_Rutherford_of_Nelson#cite_note-nobelprize-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> for which he remains the first <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Canada\" title=\"Canada\">Canadian<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Oceania\" title=\"Oceania\">Oceanian<\/a> Nobel laureate, and the only laureate born in the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/South_Island\" title=\"South Island\">South Island<\/a>.<\/p><p>Rutherford moved in 1907 to the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Victoria_University_of_Manchester\" title=\"Victoria University of Manchester\">Victoria University of Manchester<\/a> (today <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Manchester\" title=\"University of Manchester\">University of Manchester<\/a>) in the UK, where he and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Thomas_Royds\" title=\"Thomas Royds\">Thomas Royds<\/a> proved that alpha radiation is <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Helium\" title=\"Helium\">helium<\/a> nuclei.<sup id=\"cite_ref-rutherford.org.nz_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ernest_Rutherford,_1st_Baron_Rutherford_of_Nelson#cite_note-rutherford.org.nz-5\"><span>[<\/span>5<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ernest_Rutherford,_1st_Baron_Rutherford_of_Nelson#cite_note-6\"><span>[<\/span>6<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> Rutherford performed his most famous work after he became a Nobel laureate.<sup id=\"cite_ref-nobelprize_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ernest_Rutherford,_1st_Baron_Rutherford_of_Nelson#cite_note-nobelprize-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> In 1911, although he could not prove that it was positive or negative,<sup id=\"cite_ref-charge_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ernest_Rutherford,_1st_Baron_Rutherford_of_Nelson#cite_note-charge-7\"><span>[<\/span>7<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> he theorized that atoms have their charge concentrated in a very small <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Atomic_nucleus\" title=\"Atomic nucleus\">nucleus<\/a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ernest_Rutherford,_1st_Baron_Rutherford_of_Nelson#cite_note-8\"><span>[<\/span>8<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> and thereby pioneered the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Rutherford_model\" title=\"Rutherford model\">Rutherford model<\/a> of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Atom\" title=\"Atom\">atom<\/a>, through his discovery and interpretation of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Rutherford_scattering\" title=\"Rutherford scattering\">Rutherford scattering<\/a> in his <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Geiger%E2%80%93Marsden_experiment\" title=\"Geiger\u2013Marsden experiment\">gold foil experiment<\/a>. He is widely credited with first \"splitting the atom\" in 1917 in a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nuclear_reaction\" title=\"Nuclear reaction\">nuclear reaction<\/a> between nitrogen and alpha particles, in which he also discovered (and named) the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Proton\" title=\"Proton\">proton<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ernest_Rutherford,_1st_Baron_Rutherford_of_Nelson#cite_note-9\"><span>[<\/span>9<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Rutherford became Director of the Cavendish Laboratory at Cambridge University in 1919. Under his leadership the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Neutron\" title=\"Neutron\">neutron<\/a> was discovered by <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_Chadwick\" title=\"James Chadwick\">James Chadwick<\/a> in 1932 and in the same year the first experiment to split the nucleus in a fully controlled manner, performed by students working under his direction, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_Cockcroft\" title=\"John Cockcroft\">John Cockcroft<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ernest_Walton\" title=\"Ernest Walton\">Ernest Walton<\/a>. After his death in 1937, he was honoured by being interred with the greatest scientists of the United Kingdom, near <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Sir_Isaac_Newton\" title=\"Sir Isaac Newton\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Sir Isaac Newton<\/a>'s tomb in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Westminster_Abbey\" title=\"Westminster Abbey\">Westminster Abbey<\/a>. The chemical element <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Rutherfordium\" title=\"Rutherfordium\">rutherfordium<\/a> (element 104) was named after him in 1997.<\/p>","name":"Ernest Rutherford","place_of_birth":"Spring Grove, near Nelson, New Zealand","place_of_death":"Cambridge, England","text":"Ernest Rutherford ,  born in New Zealand , Chemistry, 1908","year":1908.0}